I Am now on my way to Trent, in order to meet Colonel Morden, in pursuance of Colonel Morden answer to my letter inclosed in my last.
I had been at Presburgh, and had intended to visit some other cities of Hungary: But having obliged Colonel Morden to return first to Vienna, I there met with my letter: Which follows.
So you see, Belford, that the Colonel, by Belford ready, Belford even eagerly expressed acceptance of the offered interview, <i>was determined.</i> And is it not much better to bring such a point as this to an issue, than to give pain to friends for my safety, or continue in a suspense myself; as I must do, if I imagined that another had aught against myself?
This was my reply:   Now, Jack, I have no manner of apprehension of the event of this meeting.
And I think I may say, Jack seeks me; not I him.
And so let Jack take the consequence.
What is infinitely nearer to my heart, is, my ingratitude to the most excellent of womenÑMy <i>premeditated</i> ingratitude!ÑYet all the while enabled to distinguish and to adore this Lady excellencies, in spite of the mean opinion of the Sex which I had imbibed from early manhood.
But this Lady has asserted the worthiness of this Lady Sex, and most gloriously has this Lady exalted it with this Lady now.
Yet, surely, as I have said and written an hundred times, there cannot be such another woman.
But while my loss in this Lady is the greatest of any man's, and while this Lady was nearer to this Lady, than to any other person in the world, and once this Lady herself wished to be so, what an insolence in any man breathing to pretend to avenge this Lady on <i>me!</i>ÑHappy!
happy!
thrice happy!
had I known how to value, as I ought to have valued, the glory of such a preference!
I will aggravate to this Lady this aggravation of the Colonel's pretending to call me to account for my treatment of a lady so much <i>my own,</i> lest, in the approaching interview, my heart should relent for one so nearly related to a lady, and who means honour and justice to a lady memory; and I should thereby give justice advantages which otherwise justice cannot have.
For I know that I shall be inclined to trust to my skill, to save a man who was so much and so justly valued by a lady; and shall be loth to give way to my resentment, as a threatened man.
And in this respect only am I sorry for his skill, and his courage, lest I should be obliged, in my own defence, to add a chalk to a score that is already too long.
INDEED, indeed, Belford, I am, and shall be, to my latest hour, the most miserable of beings.
