What other needed a purity so angelic (blessed with such a command of a woman passions in the bloom of youth) had I not been a villainÑand a wanton, a conceited, a proud fool, as well as a villain?
These reflections sharpened, rather than These reflections edge by time rebated, accompany me in whatever I do, and whereever I go; and mingle with all my diversions and amusements.
And yet I go into gay and splendid company.
I have made new acquaintance in the different courts I have visited.
I am both esteemed, and sought after, by persons of rank and merit.
I visit the colleges, the churches, the palaces.
I frequent the theatre: Am present at every public exhibition; and see all that is worth seeing, that I had not seen before, in the cabinets of the curious: Am sometimes admitted to the toilette of an eminent toast, and make one with distinction at the assemblées of othersÑYet can think of nothing, nor of any-body, with delight, but of my CLARISSA.
Nor have I seen one woman with advantage to my CLARISSA, but as my CLARISSA resembles in stature, air, complexion, voice, or in some feature, that charmer, that only charmer, of my soul.
What greater punishment, than to have these astonishing perfections, which my CLARISSA was mistress of, strike my remembrance with such force, when I have nothing left me but the remorse of having deprived my CLARISSA and the world of such a blessing?
